defs.docs:
Simple time handling.

 # Usage

 This crate is [on crates.io](https://crates.io/crates/time) and can be
 used by adding `time` to the dependencies in your project's `Cargo.toml`.

 ```toml
 [dependencies]
 time = "0.1"
 ```

 And this in your crate root:

 ```rust
 extern crate time;
 ```

 This crate uses the same syntax for format strings as the [strftime()]
 (http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man3/strftime.3.html) function from the C
 standard library.

sig.text: const MIN: Duration = Duration{secs: i64::MIN / MILLIS_PER_SEC - 1,          nanos:              NANOS_PER_SEC +                  ((i64::MIN % MILLIS_PER_SEC) as i32) * NANOS_PER_MILLI,};

defs.name: MAX
defs.docs: The maximum possible `Duration`: `i64::MAX` milliseconds.

sig.text: const MAX: Duration = Duration{secs: i64::MAX / MILLIS_PER_SEC,          nanos: ((i64::MAX % MILLIS_PER_SEC) as i32) * NANOS_PER_MILLI,};

defs.name: OutOfRangeError
defs.docs:
Represents error when converting `Duration` to/from a standard library
 implementation

 The `std::time::Duration` supports a range from zero to `u64::MAX`
 *seconds*, while this module supports signed range of up to
 `i64::MAX` of *milliseconds*.

defs.name: Timespec
defs.docs:
A record specifying a time value in seconds and nanoseconds, where
 nanoseconds represent the offset from the given second.

 For example a timespec of 1.2 seconds after the beginning of the epoch would
 be represented as {sec: 1, nsec: 200000000}.

defs.name: tm_isdst
defs.docs:
Daylight Saving Time flag.

 This value is positive if Daylight Saving Time is in effect, zero if
 Daylight Saving Time is not in effect, and negative if this information
 is not available.

defs.name: tm_utcoff
defs.docs:
Identifies the time zone that was used to compute this broken-down time
 value, including any adjustment for Daylight Saving Time. This is the
 number of seconds east of UTC. For example, for U.S. Pacific Daylight
 Time, the value is -7*60*60 = -25200.
